#. type: Title =====
#: kraft.adoc:762
#, no-wrap
msgid "PDF Watermark Funktionality"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: kraft.adoc:765
msgid ""
"The first, and easiest way to add a logo and other details on the print out "
"is to use the so called PDF Watermark option."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: kraft.adoc:767
msgid ""
"That means that the generated document, which does not contain a logo at "
"all, is merged with another PDF into one doc. The so called watermark "
"feature requires an otherwise empty PDF page of the same size as your "
"generated document, that has the logo printed at the right position. It can "
"be created with a text processor that can export PDF."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: kraft.adoc:769
msgid ""
"In the Kraft doc type settings dialog, the watermark options for a specific "
"doc type can be selected. The watermark PDF file can be selected and either "
"be applied to the first page only, or to every page of the generated "
"document."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: kraft.adoc:771
msgid ""
"Once set up, Kraft automatically merges the generated document with the "
"watermark PDF. The result document contains the content of both documents "
"merged together. This is not only useful for logos, but also other details "
"in the document footer."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =====
#: kraft.adoc:772
#, no-wrap
msgid "CSS Directives for Pages"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: kraft.adoc:775
msgid ""
"The second option is to use the CSS directive for page content on printed "
"HTML pages. This only works with weasyprint based doc generation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: kraft.adoc:777
msgid ""
"It uses Cascading Style Sheet (CSS) directives for paged media. CSS uses the "
"`@page` keyword to define attributes of the page on which the content is "
"printed. Weasyprint makes heavy use of that, for example to define the page "
"size."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: kraft.adoc:779
msgid ""
"In the Kraft default template for weasyprint called `invoice.gtmpl` this "
"page section can be found:"
msgstr ""

#. type: source
#: kraft.adoc:789
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"@page {\n"
"    size: A4;\n"
"    margin-left: 2.4cm;\n"
"    margin-top:27mm;\n"
"    margin-right: 1.6cm;\n"
"    margin-bottom: 2cm;\n"
"    color: #2f590a;\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: source
#: kraft.adoc:791
msgid ""
"which defines the page size to be A4, with the given margins and a default "
"text color."
msgstr ""

#. type: source
#: kraft.adoc:793
msgid ""
"To add a logo on in the top left corner of the first page of the result doc, "
"the following snippet could be added:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: kraft.adoc:799
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"@page :first {\n"
"  margin-top: 20mm;\n"
"  margin-bottom: 3cm;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: kraft.adoc:806
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  @top-left {\n"
"    content: url(/home/miller/miller_logo_s1.png);\n"
"    width:3cm;\n"
"    height: 1cm;\n"
"  }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: kraft.adoc:809
msgid ""
"This displays the top left content only on the first page, and also assigns "
"a different top- and bottom margin to the first page. Note that the content "
"url in the example is a local path, but any valid URL can be used."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: kraft.adoc:811
msgid ""
"A more fine granular way of placing the logo can be achieved by placing an "
"`img` tag into the template like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: kraft.adoc:815
#, no-wrap
msgid "<img id=\"logo\" src=\"file:///path/to/your/logo.png\" />\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: kraft.adoc:818
msgid "The CSS code to place the logo accordingly is like"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: kraft.adoc:831
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"/*\n"
" * Absolut positioned logo\n"
" */\n"
"img#logo {\n"
"  position: absolute;\n"
"  right: 0px;\n"
"  top: -100px;\n"
"  width: 178px;\n"
"  z-index: -1;\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: kraft.adoc:834
msgid ""
"With that, the logo is independent from the @page positioning from the first "
"example."
msgstr ""

